		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Treeslayer wrote:<BR><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
JazzyJoyce wrote:<BR>
<DIV>"So, getting back on topic, before someone says the gap between group and raid gear is too big, they should have at least decent group obtainable gear. Otherwise people are likely to discount what they say, because their perspective is skewed."</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>How can you skew it?&nbsp; You just get the best gear available for group/raid, and put it on a Magelo. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ffff00>So you're trying to tell me, that a 6khp, bazaar geared warrior would really have any idea if the difference between a 12k 2400ac warrior and a 18k 3600ac warrior is overpowering? And in all honesty, there is not one single warrior that has 18khp 3600ac. The only warriors with 3600ac, have about&nbsp;14k hp, and Gster only has 16600hp and 3150ac.</FONT></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#993300>No, I am saying a 6khp, Bazaar geared warrior is able to figure out what the gap actually is. Far as if there is a warrior with 18k or not, have you used the best available raid gear, or just what the highest one with a magelo has? This is important, since everyone expects the casual to have the best of what's available for them, instead of what they actually have on.</FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#993300></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Using a Warrior, you come up with something like a 12k HP/ 2400AC tank, and with say an Anguish toon, it's around 18k HP, 3600? AC, which isn't in itself that overpowering. The gap hasn't decreased, nor increased, from what I have learned, in year's. Making it sound like it's been decreased more today then ever is not really true, nor is it true that it's actually getting bigger, percentage wise. Bassically, it's around a 50% increase (from information provided on forums right here on this sight) going from Casual to Raid gear. Casual's could use some more focus type effects though. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ffff00>The difference is, while the theoretical maximum difference&nbsp;could be&nbsp;still 50% (although it seems unlikely that the top warriors in the game are so far off the max), the group gear has gotten MASSIVELY easier to get. In one single, half hour event, a group of SIX can ALL get a 200 hp/mana item, PLUS get an extra item from the chest. In a MM that takes under 1 minute to complete,&nbsp;you can get a 140hp/135 mana range item. In the last year,&nbsp;I have gotten something like 10 gear upgrades, not counting augments. Only one of these was a 300hp/mana base item. There are already people wearing every new group item from the DoD arcs. You'd be hard pressed to find many raiders with more than 1 or 2 DoD raid items, while most have none. Yes, the theoretical maximums are 30-40% apart, but the group max is so much easier to obtain, that it is almost ridiculous to compare.</FONT></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#993300>Some of the group items are easier to obtain, the other slot's are not so easy to obtain, things like Cultural are still better for certain gear slots, and takes a bit more then just looting a chest to get. If one has all the drops they can get as a casual from Missions, they don't have a full set, nor are they at maximum. This is missinformation, and should only be used for what it is, 6 to 10 upgrades, and without the upgrades, not completely do-able by just any Casual player. </FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#993300></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I think as the number's get BIGGER, the GAP Itself starts to widen in gameplay, not actually gear we are playing in. At some point this 50% (give or take) will have to start to get smaller, to keep things balanced within a reasonable gaming experience. As time goes on, you could end up with something like Raider 30k HP, Casual 20k. 10k will be an unexceptable difference, yet there will be those still playing/raiding wanting this HUGE gap in power, no matter what, or for just the sake of the desire to be an EQ god to most... Which isn't all that much of a bad thing at all, just not acceptable.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ffff00>There is no more difference between a 30k warrior and a 20k warrior, than there was between a 3k warrior, and a 2k warrior, except in your perceptions. There is, however, a huge difference between the 1400aa warrior, and the 200aa warrior, which is what most people THINK is being caused by gear.</FONT></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV>Yes, 1400aa's vs. 200aa is a HUGE difference. However, I doubt one with 1400aa's with 20k HP is going to even come close to what a 30k tank can achieve, tank, etc. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>There is a big difference between 2k vs. 3k, and 20k vs. 30k. The gap is 1k difference in the former, 10k difference in the latter. That is a 10k gap compared to a 1k gap, no matter how you figure it out.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>A 6k tank is going to be able to tank somewhat closer to what a 9k tank, then what it is today, with only gear being the difference in either (AA's can be gained by either, so that eliminates AA's from the debate).</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I do not thing that the gap is too wide right now, but I believe it could end up that way. For some reason it seem's like people are thinking that if the gap did get wider and wider, then the only one's that it would effect is the Casual player. I believe it would hurt the Raider more then anyone at all, but that's a different debate altogether. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I do think some revisions could be made currently, but the gap isn't too wide, if your looking at the best from both worlds. I think Re-itemizing old zones/quests, and the fact that the Pro's (raider's) group up in the same zones as the Amateur's (Casual's), is what 'cause's the perception of this gap being so wide... IF your a casual looking for some upgrade drops in WoS for example, and you see a Warrior in there solo'ing, it gives the impression that this is the norm' for raiding warrior's in that content (WoS), since they are there and not in Rss, etc. It's not an actual depiction of where the gap stands, since WoS is not the best available stuff for Casuals, and that solo'ing Warrior is not raiding WOS, but more then likely Anguish+ content. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>It's not fair to look at some of the best Raider's and compare them to a mid gear'd casual. It's also unfair to compare the best a Casual can obtain with less then the best Raid gear. Both leave the wrong impression.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The gap will be too wide, when the best Casual can barely survive, and the best gear'd Raider walks through it like they were all green. The gap never needs to be that drastic. However, you can't say it's that drastic unless you do have all the best Casual stuff and still have a problem doing YOUR job. You also have to have all the AA's as well, as AA's are an important part in class progression. Playing a Warrior gives a really clear idea of what a couple 100 AA's does without one upgrade. </DIV>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							"One falsehood destroys a thousand truths." "Do not think of yourself higher than you ought to think" "If you are not guilty of the robbery then you should not hold on to the loot!" -NOEL BRYSON, Ph The wise discuss ideas, the normal discuss events, the ignorant discuss other's.<br>"If you can't say something nice, say something productive, if you can't say something productive, say something intelligent. If you can't manage that, then by all means, just stop talking" - Golgolath
							</div>
								
