<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&message.id=146859#M146859">217</a> of 832
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 1163 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Treeslayer wrote:<BR><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Pouncequickk wrote:<BR><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Cellan wrote:<BR>
<DIV>The gear gap between raiders and casuals isn't too wide and getting out of hand.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The gear gap between people that don't put much effort to improve their gear and raiders is as big as ever.....but who cares because the fault in that lies with the former.</DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV>
<P>The way you word that is that if&nbsp;they do not raid you are not 'put(ing) much effort to improve their gear.' Regardless of the effort it takes to raid, people do not raid because it takes more effort to get gear if you raid, but because past a certain point, it takes less effort to get better gear in that manner. Where that 'certain point' lies is the basis for this discussion.</P>
<P>Pouncequick</P><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV>
<P>No, it really takes more effort. I've gotten a total of 10 item upgrades in the last year raiding 3-5 days a week. It's just that the rewards are better.</P>
<P>But you're missing his point. He's saying that a non-raider CAN get very nice gear. The people complaining about the "gap being too large" are the ones running around in ornate, full mithril, and WoS drops.</P>
<P>Show me ONE instance where it is more difficult to obtain a group drop, than it is to get serially flagged and geared through the entire raid progression, to the point at which you start receiving better than group quality drops (Txevu+). </P><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV>
<P>Correct me if I am wrong, but this thread started out with Kvy complaining that the gap was getting too narrow, and citing the quality of a few aug drops in Illsalin and Demiplane as proof. That he misused the language in his title may confuse the issue, but that is what he was saying. </P>
<P>Illsalin and Demiplane are hardly trivial zones, and the times I have been successful hunting&nbsp;in Illsalin&nbsp;it has been with raiders, not casuals (I am not in Demiplane yet).</P>
<P>As for the effort it takes though, DoN missions help a lot, but when you were citing DoN tradeskilled armour in your earlier post, how are you managing 1 scale every 5 hours, let alone one per person every 5 hours? Note that it takes more than one scale per piece, particularly when you add the augs, combine difficulty (assuming you can find/afford a sufficiently competent smith), etc.</P>
<P>Even with DoN vendor gear, the top augs are 680 crystals each. That is rather a lot of creator missions (approx 20 each). </P>
<P>It is true there is a lot of time put in flagging, etc, for raids, but you are more likely to get gear improvements as drops, and once you can farm them, they happen pretty quickly. In addition, you can do anything a casual can in your off raiding hours, and do so quicker/easier/more efficiently due to the better gear.</P>
<P>Many raiders look at how easy group tasks are given their gear and forget how different it is with casual gear. I have seen this in the past grouping with some such raiders... they kept talking down to me as if I&nbsp;was somehow a lesser person because my gear could not keep up. In the case I remember best, it was not that I was insufficient for the zone... it was a 65 normal LDoN. The raiders were sufficent that they were effectively duetting the mission with no healer (a couple of them were afk for RL reasons for half the mission, one of those was the healer).</P>
<P>Note not all raiders act that way. In my case I stayed non-guilded and a non-raider for a long time in great part because of such unfriendly attitudes though.</P>
<P>I do feel that gear should be earned, no matter how it is obtained, but again, if the gap is too great it is not so easy to earn as you claim.</P>
<P>And again, this thread is not about casuals saying 'give us good stuff' or 'give us raid stuff,' but ensuring that casuals can aspire to hunt hunting zones without either having to raid to hunt there or having the zones trivialized by raid gear.</P>
<P>Pouncequick</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>	
		</td></tr>
