<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&message.id=146867#M146867">220</a> of 832
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 1135 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>Pounce,</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>You make a logical fallacy though.... </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Raiders have raid level gear</DIV>
<DIV>Raiders suceed in those zones </DIV>
<DIV>Therefore the raid level gear caused their sucess</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>You assume that the gear is what makes those raiders successful in those zones.&nbsp;&nbsp; While it helps, it's not what causes the success mostly is a combination of things, which may or may not include the gear.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I am living proof that this is not the case, when during the 2nd week of Gates of discord, i was challenged that I couldn't beat tipt without time level gear.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I and my group pulled an entire set of VT gear out of the bank and went and beat it.&nbsp;&nbsp; There's basic traits that raiders tend to share, due to the raiding experience.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>1. The desire to learn and analyze, even during failure, no, especially during failue, to seek and correctly identify failure points and correct them "on the next go".&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Raiders tend to be a lot more tolerant of failue than non raiders, it's almost the most important difference between the two groups.&nbsp;&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>2. Experience with content which forces them to view encounters as entire encounters, able to identify earlier, the "dirty tricks" that are a result of the way&nbsp;encounters are designed and adapt to them without it being immediately obvious.&nbsp;&nbsp; Raiders will invariably apply a 'it's like X encounter' filter into their reaction, and move into the mode of play which best suits the little tricks that said encounter provides.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>3. The willingness to put complete trust into those you group with to perform their jobs, and knowing that they can react appropriately to those experiences.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I've done many of the DoD missions with pickup groups, and have done them with raid level groups (both of my own guild and other guilds) and the differences in play are remarkable.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I've had group level guests in all raider groups who have literally sent tells going "I never would've believed that we could've pulled that off had I not seen it myself", and that's basically from doing what we normally do on raids.... picking the right sequence of skills and disciplines, understanding exactly when one of the several mobs is going to break from me and go after X party member, when it's ok to let a shaman exit the world of debuffage and healing and to become a tank, and so on and so on.&nbsp;&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>On the other hand, I have a lot of guildies that have twinks that are geared out the wazoo, who I refuse to group with, as they don't have the right AA's, the right "feel", the conditioning to understand what's necessary to defeat an encounter, and thus I won't group with them in these encounters, as the possibility of success is minimized.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>It's not nearly "about the gear"... it really is a lot more.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I can do a whole lot more with a group of raiders in cruddy gear than I can with twinks or non raiders in the best gear.</DIV>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							<img src="http://i12.photobucket.com/albums/a247/Ridefort/frodsig.gif" height=110 width=300><br><br>Warrior Class Correspondent<br>"54 random people is no more a raid than a heap of building materials is a house"
							</div>
								
